Introduction
For this project, I decided to work with nginx because it’s a simple, lightweight web server that behaves a lot like the real services a sysadmin would manage in production. It’s easy to install, easy to restart, and—most importantly for this assignment—it gives me clear signals I can check before and after a change. Since the goal is to practice building a reliable, verifiable runbook, nginx felt like the right balance between “real enough to matter” and “simple enough to experiment with safely.”
Another reason I chose nginx is because the assignment specifically mentions that “a throwaway nginx… on a lab VM is plenty.” That told me I didn’t need to overthink it or build something complicated. I just needed a service I could actually run, break, fix, and verify on my own machine. Nginx fits that perfectly.
Before I started writing the runbook, I made sure my Ubuntu VM was fully ready. I updated the package list with sudo apt update, installed nginx using sudo apt install nginx -y, and checked that the service was running with systemctl status nginx. After that, I used curl http://localhost to confirm that nginx was actually serving a page and returning a 200 OK. Once all of that worked, I knew the environment was stable and that I could safely restart the service, test failures, and verify health checks as required by the project.

What I Built
The core deliverable was a shell script (verify.sh) that performs a basic health check on nginx. The script tests two things: whether the nginx service is active, and whether it returns a successful HTTP status code when accessed locally. If both conditions are met, the script prints a “healthy” message; otherwise, it reports an unhealthy state. I also created a runbook describing how to execute the script, how to interpret the results, and how to intentionally break nginx to test the failure path. The project required capturing both a healthy run and an unhealthy run, which I completed by stopping the nginx service and observing the script’s behavior.

In addition to the script and runbook, I produced a copilot_policy.yaml file that defines the boundaries of AI involvement. This policy outlines the autonomy ladder, the tasks Copilot is allowed to assist with, and the guardrails that ensure a human remains accountable for all decisions and actions.

Where the AI Helped
it helped me draft the initial version of the verification script. I already understood the logic — check the service, check the HTTP response — but Copilot accelerated the process by suggesting a clean structure and safe quoting practices. It also helped me refine the script to make it more readable and consistent.

Where the AI Hallucinated
Although Copilot was helpful, it did hallucinate at times. One example occurred when I asked about the linter output. Because ShellCheck produced no warnings, Copilot initially assumed it might have missed something and suggested that ShellCheck “usually prints warnings.” In reality, ShellCheck prints nothing when the script is clean. This wasn’t a major issue, but it showed that the AI sometimes fills in gaps with assumptions.

My Verdict on Trusting This Copilot
Based on this project, I would trust Copilot in specific, limited ways. I trust it to:

draft scripts, documentation, and policies

explain concepts clearly

suggest improvements

help me think through problems

I do not trust it to:

run commands

make decisions

validate correctness

detect logic errors

operate without human review

Copilot is excellent at accelerating work, but it is not a substitute for understanding. It can propose solutions, but it cannot guarantee they are correct or safe. For this reason, I would place Copilot at autonomy rung 1 for most technical tasks: it may suggest, but I must review every line before using it.

In a real production environment, I would be even more cautious. I would never allow Copilot to restart services, modify configurations, or act autonomously. It is a drafting and reasoning tool — not an operator.

Honest AI Usage Note
I used Microsoft Copilot throughout this project to help draft the verification script, explain concepts, and format the copilot_policy.yaml file. All AI‑generated content was reviewed, edited, and approved by me. The final decisions, testing, and verification were performed manually. No commands were executed by the AI, and all work was completed with a human in the loop.
